### Bench-driven follow-ups (round 202605101036 overnight benches)

Twenty-nine benches landed in `mock/benches/` overnight. Several
findings touch this crate's providers (AdaptWu, EMA, default Kits).
Index: `mock/benches/NIGHT_FINDINGS_2026-05-11.md`.

**AdaptWu EMA formulation validated.** The `ema_formulation` bench
confirms audit-2 M4: Q0.32 saturating fixed-point EMA via
`NORM_7_OVER_8` + `NORM_1_OVER_8` is the empirically correct shape.
It beats f32 IIR by 11-14% at N≥1024 on aarch64 (Q0.32: 2113→1895
at N=1024; 35999→31198 at N=16384; -14% gap stable). The marked-as-
correct design call in `mock/design_rounds/202605101036_topic.thread-pool.md`
S7 (audit-2 amendment) is bench-validated.

**AdaptWu reduction shape.** The `fold_strategy` bench (largest
finding of the night) shows quad-way interleaved-accumulator reduction
is ~3.8x faster than single-acc sequential on mul-heavy reductions
at N=16384. LLVM does NOT auto-extract this ILP. If AdaptWu's
multi-fiber metric aggregation is implemented as a single-accumulator
sweep over PassDurationMetrics or similar, it pays a 2-4x latency
tax. Follow-up: AdaptWu's metric aggregation should use the
interleaved-accumulator shape (parked upstream as `arvo::Fold`
trait family).

**fetch_add counter shape validated.** The `atomic_inc_strategy`
bench confirms `fetch_add(1, Relaxed)` beats CAS-loop by 11-19% via
LSE LDADD on aarch64. AdaptWu's call-count increment counters and
the phase-barrier centralised-counter in Topic 6 axis I should use
`fetch_add` directly (no CAS-loop trait abstraction). Bench file:
`mock/benches/atomic_inc_strategy_n*_findings.md`.

**Per-fiber inline metrics atomic envelope.** The `atomic_vs_plain`
bench confirms `AtomicU64+Relaxed` is free in single-thread
non-contended code on aarch64. AdaptMetrics fields exposed as
`AtomicU64` cost nothing in the hot path AS LONG AS the per-fiber
cache-line invariant holds (Topic 3 M3). Cache-line invariant is
the design's responsibility; the bench validates the cost claim.

**Norm-as-FastFloat caveat.** Surprising `float_width` finding: on
aarch64, f32 and f64 are essentially identical (~3% delta);
i64-fixed-point is 25-62% SLOWER on FMA-shape reductions. The
StandardAdaptKit's pick of `arvo::Norm<S=Warm>` (Q0.32-shaped) for
EMA-driven decisions wins on the IIR shape (per `ema_formulation`)
but does NOT auto-win on the FMA-shape per-fiber aggregation
(per `float_width`). Different inner-loop shapes favor different
strategies. The arvo strategy-marker docs follow-up tracks this
nuance.
